            {
                "comment_id": 4,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 1,
                "content": "This is making me a bit anxious as a first-time buyer \ud83d\ude1f Is the 8% dip mainly in prime areas (Palm, Downtown, DIFC), or is it spilling over into mid-market communities like JVC, Town Square, Dubai South? And the 22% drop in DLD volumes\u2014could that be Ramadan/Eid seasonality, or does it look like a broader slowdown?\n\nI\u2019m saving for my first apartment and worried about taking on a mortgage. If this trend continues, do you think developers or banks might offer better incentives or lower rates? Are rents softening at all, or still rising?\n\nTrying to decide whether to wait a few months or move ahead this summer. Any data on Q2 pre-sales, off-plan cancellations, or mortgage approvals would really help. Thank you!",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:57:16.224965",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 5,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 6,
                "content": "6 years renting in Dubai and perpetually on the fence about buying. This 8% QoQ dip gives me hope but also makes me worry it could be the start of something bigger. For those who track DLD data closely: is the 22% volume drop concentrated in prime/secondary or broad-based across communities? \n\nIf this is a healthy correction, would you start shortlisting/negotiating now or wait a couple more quarters? I\u2019m visa-dependent so liquidity matters\u2014safer to go ready with ~25% down + fixed-rate mortgage vs off-plan 50/50 payment plan? \n\nAreas I\u2019m watching: JVC, Sports City, Town Square, and older Marina stock. Do you expect rents to soften next or will they lag 6\u20139 months? Any de-risking tips (bigger emergency fund, higher DP, fixed-rate lock)? \n\nTrying not to let FOMO drive this, so would love perspective from folks who bought in 2020\u201321 vs recent buyers. Thank you!",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:57:22.603025",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 6,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 11,
                "content": "Initial take from a GCC real estate/REITs analyst: an 8% QoQ move in \u201cprime\u201d can be skewed by a few thin super-prime prints; the 22% drop in volumes also overlaps with Ramadan/Eid timing and a broader risk-off. Feels more like cooling than a regime shift\u2014for now. What I\u2019m watching:\n\n- Off-plan vs ready mix: if off-plan share (>50\u201360% lately) slows, developers may pace launches. Track absorption and payment plan aggressiveness.\n- Mortgage vs cash: Dubai remains cash-heavy. If mortgage approvals soften while cash buyers hold, impact is more contained than in HK/SG cycles.\n- Yields and rents: prime gross yields have compressed toward ~3\u20134% in some pockets. If rent growth plateaus, cap rate expansion implies further price softness in prime before mid-market.\n- Supply/handovers: H2 handovers rising in certain submarkets; true \u201cprime\u201d supply remains tight. Expect more pressure in upper-mid segments than ultra-prime villas.\n\nEquities angle: developers with larger recurring income and strong balance sheets (e.g., Emaar, Aldar) should be more resilient than pure off-plan names; slower price inflation can actually normalize volumes and churn. Key data next: DLD weekly transactions (off-plan vs secondary), cancellation rates, developer collections, and any moderation in rental growth.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 08:00:08.223185",
