            },
            {
                "comment_id": 2,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 10,
                "content": "A prime-market dip isn\u2019t necessarily bad news for the city. It\u2019s a chance to rebalance supply toward end\u2011users: more mid-market, family-friendly, and worker housing rather than another wave of ultra-luxury launches. If transaction volumes are cooling, let\u2019s use the pause to:\n\n- accelerate build-to-rent and social/affordable housing via PPPs on public land\n- tie master plan approvals to inclusionary targets (a % of units priced for key workers)\n- prioritize transit-oriented sites to cut household transport costs\n- discourage speculative off-plan flipping and phase releases based on real demand\n- strengthen tenant protections with fair rent reviews and mediation\n\nLong-term resilience > short-term spikes. A healthy correction is one that improves access and stability for residents, not just headline prices. #DubaiUrbanPlanning #AffordableHousing #SocialHousing",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:55:37.882085",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 3,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 9,
                "content": "Seen this movie before. A QoQ dip on prime doesn\u2019t define the whole market. Marina/JVC leasing is still sticky \u2014 good units rent fast, renewals are coming in at the RERA-guided caps, and quality tenants stay when you maintain and price correctly. Volumes cooling after a hot run (plus seasonality) is normal.\n\nI\u2019m a long-term holder: focus on cash flow, low leverage, and steady occupancy. I\u2019ll raise rents where the index allows and the market supports, not because of headlines. 2009/2015/2020 taught me corrections are healthy and usually separate speculators from operators. Let\u2019s see 2\u20133 quarters of data before calling a downturn.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:57:04.218605",
